          "body": "Verse 9 is the psalm's pastoral hinge from proclamation to personal commitment: 'But as for me, I will declare it forever; I will sing praises to the God of Jacob.' The Hebrew grammar here is emphatic — 'but as for me' (wa'ani) sets Asaph apart from both the arrogant warned in verses 4-5 and the wicked condemned in verse 8. He is neither boasting in self nor drinking the cup of wrath. He is declaring and singing. The vow is total: 'forever' (olam). And the recipient of praise is named specifically — 'the God of Jacob.' Not an abstract philosophical first principle, not a generic divine power, but the God who met Jacob at Bethel (Genesis 28:10-22), who wrestled with him at Peniel (Genesis 32:24-30), who kept the covenant through all of Jacob's moral failure and geographical displacement. This is the God who judges the arrogant and vindicates the humbled — precisely because He is the covenant-keeping God of a specific people and a specific history. The psalm moves from thanksgiving (v.1) through crisis (the boastful's arrogance, vv.4-5) through certainty (the cup, v.8) to doxology (v.9), tracing the path every believer must walk in the gap between observed injustice and the moed of divine judgment."
